demand: It was interesting to see how I reacted to the offers when I was trying to be even, but interesting to see that I changed my approach following this
comment: It was very professional and simple to follow instructions. A little bit repetitive and long though.

demand: The experiment seemed to be about greed, and how one can gain more money by enticing others by offering more money to one participant than another.
comment: The experiment overall was interesting, it definitely makes you wonder and have questions behind why and how another person splits the money. On a personal level it allows you to question and affirm your morals in terms of what you think is fair or what you think is perhaps not so fair.
degree: Latin American Studies with Human Rights

comment: It was interesting to see that some people were willing to share while others were not. Sometimes it took a while for I could continue with the experiment.

demand: How people's (political) views influence their behavior when they are asked to share money and whether they put themselves as first priority.

demand: I believe the experiment aims to identify how people will negotiate different monetary offers when they are not face to face with one another. It also aims to determine how fairly people will split odd amounts of money when participants are not in direct contact with one another.
comment: I found the experiment to be interesting and I actually learned something about myself. To begin with I tried to split the money as equally as possible but when I saw that other people were offering larger amounts to themselves I began to conform and do the same.

demand: Analysing how people make decision in different situations. how people react, when it comes to money
comment: it was fun and enjoyable, but a bit boring because i had to wait a long to for the experiment to continue

demand: How greedy/generous people are when it comes to sharing money
comment: I feel that the experiment went well and that people are fairer than i thought they would be

demand: It took long, but I feel the experiment was about what we think of modern world with the money, then how our mentality was towards money.

comment: The participants in my group were not as greedy as I was
degree: BA International Relations with Modern Languages

demand: whether one of the people that were not selected takes the offer even if the third person doesnt get anything, or gets very little. it was based on ethical and moral principles in economic settings, showing how when all 3 work together they actually achieve  more
comment: it took too long for people to answer, too much waiting! interesting concept though
it was a very good experiment in terms of seeing how personal gain affects decision making and how other people respond to your idea of a fair proposal

demand: IT WAS POLITICAL STANDPOINTS AND THE REALITY HOW OUR ACTUAL BEHAVIOUR DIFFERS OR ALIGNS WITH POLITICAL OR MORAL COMPASS.

comment: Interesting to see that everyone is self-centered

demand: I think the experiment was about equality and people with power have the ability to sort out any kind of money between the population, i.e the government.
comment: It was simple and easy to understand and follow, however there was a bit of a delay at one point. It was good overall.

demand: The experiment was about seeing how people act and treat others when they have a certain amount of power (in this case indicated by money and by the fact that the can not be traced back or identified and that every time the people you relate with change). demand: In my opinion the experiment was about making financial decisions in different situations
comment: I think this experiment could be very helpful for those who carry out studies about this kind of things
I thought it was well structured and enjoyable.

demand:

demand: How fair people are in sharing wealth.

comment: A good way to test if an individual is sharing

demand: how people take decisions in different situations
comment: it was interesting and challenging, but confusing at first

demand: Our thought processes when it comes to political elements of society and how this influences the way we share assets eg. money
comment: Confusing at first but I understood it after the first round. Interesting and thought provoking concept

demand: I think it's about how much money someone is willing to give to another but is willing to keep for themselves and maybe if their value for money contrasts their political values.
comment: I enjoyed it! Granted I got the short straw in most of the stages but I found it interesting.

demand: Seeing if different race, gender or political views affected how people would split a set amount of money in a group.
comment: I think the experiment was a good idea though most of the proposals I received seemed to be similar. It was easy to do and had simple, easy to follow instructions.

demand: I believe this experiment was to do in part with whether or not people would be more generous with giving money if the participant were in a similar place to them on the political scale.
comment: The other participants were generous in their offerings, however I believe the offers were never rejected because the allowance would then go down.

demand: I think its about how people react in groups when money is involved. Whether people will comply or settle for certain amounts if it means not losing out on a larger amount. or whether pride or greed will get in the way if a too low amount is offered to an individual. It my also be to see if race affects the decisions made by individuals.
comment: I thought it was an interesting experiment, especially since no one knows the individuals in the groups.

demand: I would think this experiment is about how people think of money and whether they believe that everyone deserves to be paid equally of if people are just focused on staying rich and therefore we have situations where the rich try and stay rich and do not think about the poor.
comment: I found this experiment to be quick and easy. There was some waiting for people to respond as we had to do 10 rounds but overall it was good.

demand: If equal opportunities are made based on their opinions given beforehand.
comment: I thought it was well-constructed to an extent. It was good to show how people react to situations that involve money, but the experiment was a bit too repetitive and the waiting time was lengthy.

demand: To see if people people from a certain perceptive offered fairer amounts and whether apparently knowing others political position changed the amount offered
comment: It was certainly interesting that in some rounds the offer would attempt to divide the money equally, while in others people essentially bribed one participant in order to gain the most amount of money for themselves, while leaving one participant with either next to or in fact nothing.

demand: Seeing if people would continue sharing their money equally after the amount begin to change. Also to see if people can work out that you only need one other person to accept the offer so you can give a low offer to the remaining person.
degree: MA Advertising, Marketing and the Media

comment: That it cant be objective firstly since university students will aim for money thus the sample is just biased to begin with, also the questions to allocate each person into a left to right bar were completely vague and I believe not representative. Overall though this experiment might represent how people with different political views would share the money differently, though it also represents how corrupt people might be because even their political views they might share the money in a different way than what their views support.

demand: How to convince people to accept a situation that they think is as good as it can be. By convincing the majority they are better off accepting the offer even though the proposing wins and the other participant loses.
comment: A good assessment of how people think about money and the lengths they will go to to get the most for themselves and ensure the proposal is accepted.

demand: About the relationship between people's stated principles and values and their observed actions.
comment: It was interesting but got rather boring since 10/10 periods i was involved in got settled in the first round and I had to do a lot of waiting.

demand: Based on someones political viewpoint how would they divide the money up.
comment: It was reasonably interesting to see how the offers changed over the 10 rounds. They tended to be pretty equal at the start to extremes at the end

demand: Under and overpaid individuals based on gender / race.
comment: Well constructed, very thorough explanation, and well ran. A little bit long in between periods, but other than that, it was good

demand: I think the experience is about relating politcal views to our beliefs on equality of pay.
comment: I couldn't help but find my own behaviour rather ego-centric at times which made me laugh. As soon as I realised that it only took one other person to accept the offer out of the three for me to obtain that money, I started to be less sharing and desired more  money for myself. Also it is better to accept an offer above <a3>5 in the first stage as you will end up with the possibility of earning much less later on. Finally, I think that my more left-minded politcal views should mean that I would rather have more equality in pay, but it just goes to show how the capitalist system gets to all of us, and when you are low on money you could even end up being unfair and do things to get you ahead of others, despite it being very selfish.

demand: Studying people's behavior in the community, focusing on how likely it is that they will share rewards with others participants.
comment: Well structured, easy to understand and interesting to participate to.

demand: Partly about how selfless people are, but also about whether someone's skin color, gender, or political views determined how much people wanted to give.
comment: It was quite long, which would be a real kick in the teeth if you leave with nothing.

demand: Linking greed to political views / opinions people have. i.e someone who's regarded as being more far right tends to act more selfishly than someone regarded as being far left.
comment: Well run and a clever idea / hypothesis, which i slowly grasped by the end in terms of if you sway one persons mind you guarantee yourself a certain amount of money however the break between voting and approving was far too long.

Intresting. Some people made sure they made the most profit out of if, by sharing their succes with one other person so that they had "power". The other then only has to accept, making them feel less guitly then if they had actually made the choice to give nothing to the third person. And the third person's decision didn't have any weight.

demand: I think the experience measured people's behavior in a specific setting, and to see how the choices developed throughout the "bidding". I do also believe the findings will be compared with one's political view and origin. And whether this matters when allocating the money.
comment: I think it was a good experience. It was a lot of waiting, but other than that it was relatively fun.

demand: how much are you willing to share out wealth, even in anon circumstances, and how this compares to your political/social etc beliefs
comment: I thought it was an interesting exercise, perhaps a little tedious as there were many trials of the same thing. It would be interesting to see how this experiment would run with actual face to face scenarios and comparing this against the computer generated samples to see if people are any less or more 'generous'

demand: how do we treat others when we their "political direction" if, and how much, this influences our behavior
comment: people seem to struggle making decisions that benefit everyone no matter political opinion

demand: I think it was about the relationship between our political and social thoughts and our economic decisions.
comment: I think that you can see that when people are in different contests they follow their istints and do not follow their political idea.

demand: Peoples tendencies to donate money based on political views and also equality or selfishness
comment: Interesting experiment, I personally liked the concept of reducing the pie value if two people disagreed with the distribution of the money

demand: The way in which our perceptions of someone else's race, gender and political views can affect our ideas of their value.
comment: It was a rather straightforward and easy to follow experiment with an interesting premise. There isn't much that can be said aside from that. I don't regret participating in it.

demand: I think it was about the way people make decisions based on what they want as compared to other. Whether people will choose to benefit only themselves or choose to benefit themselves and others (relatively) equally, similar to game theory.
comment: It was ok, for the most part it seemed people were genuinely choosing to benefit all rather than choosing to benefit themselves solely. Some of the participants however took very long in making their decisions as a lot of the time i found myself having to wait for them to proceed, sometimes upwards of 3-4 minutes.

demand: At first it was about political and ethical views but later i believe it was more about fairness and/or selfishness.
comment: I have no opinion on this question.

demand: how people react when put into difficult monetary situations
how fair is a society, do we think that each person has an equal chance of winning extra.
comment: that it was fair and yet still people managed to abuse the system to get more money than other people because of the fear of getting less money if they do not comply.

demand: How money affects how people treat each other?
comment: It was okay but annoyingly long

demand: Gathering information about how individuals react towards making instant decisions without any prior information.
comment: It is a valuable experience in terms of knowing my own reactions when being introduced to such environment.

demand: The experiment was about equality. I think it was to do with how our political views influence our decision making.
comment: I enjoyed the experiment as I felt it engaged and encouraged me to approach to it from a tactical viewpoint.

demand: I believe it was about the economic behaviour of people according to their ethnicity.
comment: It was interesting although a bit long

demand: Politics? How different race and political status affect economic status?
comment: Interesting, but would be nice to know the purpose of it

demand: It was to see who I would give more or less money to based on their gender and ethnicity based on my political views of their social standing from my political standpoint.

How rational decisions are made and whether the amount given to each person affected their decisions in anyway. 
This may be due to either happiness for getting a larger share, or annoyance for getting the least or nothing between the three people.
comment: This experiment was alright. Its however, the waiting interval that seemed to have dragged for a bit (when the computer was generating random numbers). This may have affected the Peoples thoughts and even end up somehow losing interest in the fun that there is in distributing money like that.

demand: Whether you support your original statement of being left/right wing. Whether race and political stance has an effect on how you would share the money
comment: I enjoyed it very much. I am very interested in further research into the social sciences and would like to take it up as a career.

demand: Whether to accept the first amount offered to you, or risk getting less by going to round 2 and so on.
comment: unfair and it showed how money is more important to some people than to others.

demand: I think the experiment is about associating people's political views with the way they distribute pay among others and seeing if there is a connection between them, since there should be.
comment: Overall, my impression of the experiment is fairly good, although I do recognize some flaws in it. This is because the people attending the experiment will all want to make as much money as possible. Ideally it would be fair if everyone received the same amount, however the capitalist society isn't fair and you should play to the best ability the cards you are given. And since making money is really important depending on your financial circumstances then it seems fairly obvious that people distribute their pay unfairly sometimes. I do realize that I may be totally wrong and that two wrongs don't make a right but in this experiment, it is the money that matters.

demand: the experiment was about whether race/ethnicity/gender had an effect on the amount of money that was shared between people and whether they though the money allocated to them was fair or not. i think this was reflected upon the current political and economic state the UK is currently in.
comment: the experiment was good, the instructions were clear and precise however there was a long waiting period inbetween each period. the experiment showed how people would share the money if they could.

demand: To see what correlation there is between political views and fairness in respect of the distribution of resources.
comment: Far too long between stages: one took 10 minutes.
degree: PhD in Computer Science (colour image processing using quaternions)

demand: How much money would people share if they know what race/skin colour belongs to.So maybe it is discrimination or sexism
comment: I thought it was interesting. it showed how greedy people can be and what factor can lead a person a person to make a particular decision in regards to money when you only know the skin colour of a person and gender

demand: I think it was about how you divide money to people with regards to their race
comment: It was good but a bit slow, and i thought some of the other participants were really unfair with their distribution of the money

demand: The generosity of people when they are anonymous, with some aspects of prejudice against race, age, gender and political views.
comment: It was a well thought out and good experiment. It wasn't surprising to see that every participant except myself was only interested in getting the most for themselves. My aim was to be as unselfish and fair as possible, and to restore justice in another negotiation if someone else was unfair in another one.
That people will always want the most for themselves

demand: Allocating money among peopl, and how people make decisions
it was about how to make different decision when there are three or more people deal with the same problem together, and the proportion of the 17 pound need to makes other agree too.
comment: i think this experiment is really helping us the think about the others and during in different situation what we should do and how to persuade another two participants to agree with you  at the same time, its also about teamwork.

demand: How people react to other people's opinions when they don't know each others identity
comment: It was good seeing how people split the money and they always seemed to give themselves the highest amount out of the three, or tired to make them as equal as possible.

demand: I think this experiment was about how we visualize people from their avatar (given to us from the computer) and sort of "judge" them based on their looks/gender and give them what we think they should have.
comment: I've never completed anything like this before, at first it was a bit peculiar, however overall it seems to be pretty interesting.
People may have taken other factors into consideration like race.
degree: Law llb with a year abroad

demand: Individual's reactions to people's political alignment and race, and the effects on their behaviour in negotiation
comment: interesting to take part in, confusing at times (cf. notes left on desk no.1)
degree: LLB in English and French Law

demand:
SHARING AND ECONOMY
BASED HOUSEHOLD INCOME
HOW THE GOVERNMENT DIVIDE MONEY
comment: PEOPLE LOOK AFTER THEMSELVES BEFORE OTHERS

demand: I think that this experiment was about political views, how money should be divided between people who have strong political views and people who don't. I also think different ethnicity and gender was questioned throughout the experiment also.
comment: I liked the experiment. It was interesting how people who seemed to have strong political views distributed the money. Also i was interested in how different ethnicity and genders distributed their money too. I am alarmed by how i distributed my money also, making decisions i would not consciously make when thinking of morals.

demand: Whether political allignment has any affect on monetary behaviour.
comment: The experiment was good, although its frustrating that other experimentees dont understand that more money can be made collectively rather than individuals being selfish and trying to take the most for themselves, forcing a new proposal where everyone gets less.

demand: I think it was about how you share money, and it is supposed to vary depending of race and political views.
comment: I found it interesting and morally complicated.

demand: To assess the way money will be allocated in the different parties. Maybe to see the inequalities in the distribution of money as well in the different political parties.
comment: It was interesting to see the different proposals.

demand: How people make decisions in groups, especially when aware of the race and political views of the rest of the group members.
comment: Interesting to participate in, I'd like to hear more about it if possible.

demand:
How people act in an anonymous situation and whether monetary greed affects this. 
For example, most people allocated the most amount of money to themselves - namely <a3>7 but in a situation where they are not anonymous, they would split it equally.
comment: The waiting periods were really long. I have so many drawings to prove this. I liked it though, other than waiting in-between the rounds

demand: The allocation of wealth according to different political views.
comment: All people noticed that is better to give everyone some amount of money, so that their allocation would be chosen. However, there was also the other strategy, where you give high amount of money to yourself and then slightly less amount to another player, leaving the third player with zero. This always won the other player's favorable vote.

demand: I believe the experiment was about how you make different decisions and allocate money to people in different scenarios. I believe it aimed to test the amount of money people will share when others have to vote and when others do not have to vote.
comment: I feel that the experiment was very interesting, however I feel that the breaks in between each negotiation round was quite long.

demand: Making economic decisions, based on the allocation of wealth and what society thinks about the current system.
comment: Interesting, as you have a say in which you have a chance to dictate how much is allocated to each person, but quite often you are able to estimate/predict the outcome based on the norms of our society, assuming everyone thinks rationally.

demand: I think experiment was about political views. If political view has anything to do with economics.
comment: I think majority of people seeks to be equal and have almost same amount of money.

demand: I think it was about deciding what is fair, what you will accept personally and what is unfair. I think a degree of selfishness or greed can be established but also how we view eachother in the sense of being equal or more needy than ones self. Also within a team, if the majority of the members are considering the need of others or agree in sharing and equality that is generally accepted and greed is not.
comment: My impression is that it can give an insight to how people with different ideas on sharing and equality think. It also can help an initially 'greedy' individual realise that equal portions may benefit you more.

demand: whether you are willing to sacrifice a part of your personal wealth in order to distribute the money equally among the 3 players in your group, or whether youre selfish and prefer to keep more for yourself
comment: it took too long, there should be a time limit for people to decide to speed up the process

demand: I think this experiment was about how people react when they are anonymous and can be either fair or try to go for their own profit first.
comment: I think it was an interesting experiment, although I think it would be more interesting if the participants numbers in the group wouldn't change, if they would actually have a sort of alter ego for the experiment, so in case someone tries to do something fishy in one round, he can be 'punished' for it the next one.
degree: BA Spanish studies with Latin American Studies

demand: To see how people would distribute wealth
comment: Its a good experiment it would be funny if you could see who chose what in certain sections AFTER the experiment is done.

demand: decision making based on both co-operation and competition
comment: interesting.  People used to playing competitive games or competing in their work would score higher.  It took me a while to work out what the results of my actions might be. Also instructions are hard to grasp

demand: I thought the experiment was about decision making and how the result of our decisions influences the choices we make. comment: It was simple enough, the only thing that was bad was the waiting in between each decision, that got tedious and I became impatient towards the end.

demand: The distrobution and in/equality of wealth
comment: I was pleasantly surprised by people

demand: How selfish and caring an individual is

comment: I think the game helps to understand that allocating a bit more money to some participants time to time, make them want to allow you have a bit more in the next round. It's all about balance.

demand: Whether people were capable of dividing money in a fair way even when there was never one.

comment: I think the experiment allows me to estimate and predict the choices other makes and what there acceptable line is. It allows me to optimize the amount of money to get in each round of experiment

demand: To see how people's fairness would change as the experiment progressed
comment: Time consuming but showed some reality

demand: i believe it was about how people behave towards others in comparison to themselves, whether if given the choices, make decisions solely based on what they want within a group rather than what what the group as a whole may want.

comment: It was well organised and interesting.

demand: About how fair we are about money when it comes to other people. We have our own interest at heart but at the same time you cannot act all selfish other group members will not accept your offer. Also our background affects our behaviour.
comment: It was alright, although I have done this once before.

demand: Generosity and equity of people on the base of their political ideas and the way they define themselves.
comment: It is difficult to be honest and and balanced at all time. You often get annoyed by other people inequity and as well political ideas of other people tend me to influence me quite much.I tend to share and being more generous with people with ideas more similar to mine. Race as well plays a role: I tend to be more generous and "equal" with black people. The last bit was the only one where I really felt in duty of being equos in the division of the 3 pounds.

demand: Knowing how each participant would want to split the money, unconsciously taking into account the gender, origin and political view of the two others. I say unconsciously because it does not really matter, but you still peak at these info to know how to share the money, to be able to gain more with one other participant and sacrificing the last one
I think this experiment was about making financial decisions in a certain situation
comment: I think it was a very interesting experiment that aims to understand how people make decisions and why

demand: Seeing whether which political party you and the other group members supported influenced how much money you gave them
how we share things according to people being like-minded.

Whether people would favor giving money to people of the same sex, the opposite sex, the same ethnic group, a different ethnic group, similar political views or different political views. Also whether the person would be selfish or share the money out more fairly between participants.
comment: It was good, other than I was not sure what the right or left party was.
A bit unfair in terms of determining how much money participants received, and the pauses in between were too long but overall okay.

demand: How people make decisions in different situations/how different people's morals effect the decisions they make.
comment: Alright, very boring waiting for everyone else to decide.

demand: I think the experiment was about voting and the way in which people decide to vote for certain parties
comment: I think it was a simple experiment which was fairly easy

demand: prejudice according to appearance and political views
comment: people were mostly kind with how they shared the money

demand: i think it was about how much you would be willing to give people that you do not know. i also think it is about greed.
comment: I thought it was interesting, especially to see how much other people were doing the same. it was also interesting to see that people were giving people nothing, just so they could accumulate more.

demand: How political views affect opinions on people, without any other knowledge about that person.
comment: It was interesting to see how people chose to allocation the funds, and I felt I was engaged in this experiment because it reminded me of a particular topic I learnt recently in my studies.

demand: how much you are willing to give to someone based on their race/gender and political views
Not too sure, perhaps about how political views influence bias towards other people?
How fairly the money would be distributed.

comment: That you are forced to make decisions based on the decisions of others

demand: To indicate how greedy people are and somehow see whether they were racist based on the fact that the images showed the race of the people involved
I think its gambling because you don't if someone is actually going to give you any money, so it is a risk you will have to take.
comment: Overall I think it was quiet fun.

demand: It reminded me of Rawls theory of Justice and splitting wealth up according to what you believe the other person should be entitled to.
comment: It was fun and interesting to see other peoples behavioural patterns and my own behaviourial patterns when sharing the money between ourselves. I believe you can have a hidden communication between people even though you dont know who they are

demand: I think it was about decision-making process and how it differs from person to person depending on their ethnic origin, sex and political orientation.
comment: I think my choices have not been influenced by the factors described above.

demand: How people would allocate wealth in an economy
comment: It was interesting to see how we as human beings have the tendency to be greedy. Politicians and money people included

demand: seeing how greedy people are when you can't see the person you're taking money away from
comment: clever as its showing how people distribute money when they think they're anonymous and no-one will ever know how much they took or gave except the people who run the experiment and analyse the data

demand: Getting to know how people make group decisions and in such a situation if they show selfishness or opt for egalitarianism.
comment: It was curious how most of the time people tended to divide the sum equally even though they did not know the people they were assigning the money to.

demand: I think that the aim of the experiment was to determine how we, as humans, make decisions that have an affect on ourselves as well as others. As we were able to see avatars that reflected the ethnicity and the gender of the other participants in our group, I feel that there may have been an extra aim: to determine whether or not race and gender have an effect upon our decision making processes.
comment: I feel that the experiment was fair, interesting and enjoyable to participate in.

demand: peoples sense of loyalty towards a particular race (perhaps their own) and loyalty towards those of a similar political view/dislike for those with different political view.

comment: I think sharing is good, but it does not work without communication with the other parts, so this experiment was frustrating, since one does not know what the others intentions are.

demand: How much money people are willing to share, depending on characteristics of the other person (race
comment: In most rounds, people were willing to share the money as equally as possible so maybe it does not give a great insight into what I believed the experiment was about.

demand: How much money one would be willing to give depending on whether they were left or right.
comment: It was interesting trying to find different combinations that people would or would not be willing to accept

demand: according to the different political views, how people hand money
comment: people allocated in the "left"side of the line tend to keep more money to themselves, even though I expected it from right side pople.

demand: dividing assets, seeing if we live up to our values and if they make a difference and if prejudice counts
comment: interesting makes you think how it works at the the top of society

demand: about seeing what people will do in these situations. whether in an anonymous situation they will try to keep as much money for themselves or whether they will try to make as much as they can by almost teaming up with one other person in their group. It can also look at whether people will be likely to take a small amount of money given or they would rather lose overall money from the pie to try again for more - how much of a risk taker are they? It can also see whether people are likely to take higher money when it is offered to them by somebody else even if it is at the expense of another of the players
comment: it was interesting to try and see what the other people in your group will do. I know I trued to push it and see how the other person in my group would react if i gave them a lot and the third player very little.

demand: It felt like it was about how we make decisions on how to devide money between us, with consideration to how much we would like to earn, and how we can do so. I like to think I am untilitarian, which is why i bid 5 for me and 6 for the others, since I would rather have 5 of 17, then 4 out of 12. but the others seemed to think differently, since they were out for making the most money for themselves, through screwing someone else over.
comment: it started out ok, but then once people got to know the system, and they knew they only had to divide the money with one person to get as much as they wanted, they continued doing so. I kept to my strategy, since I believe that people would make better decisions in real life, when they know how their actions might affect another person, but it was frustrating to be the one with only 1.5 or even just 1 left at the end.

demand: How people treat one another and their views on equality.

It was about the allocation of limited resources and specifically about how people would distribute those resources and how the majority would react if expose to different situations of more or less fair distribution.
comment: Since there is no need of unanimity, the 2/3 majority decides how to distribute the resources, which can lead to unequal distribution of the total pie. However, there was a tendency towards a distribution that tried not to let someone way behind. On the other hand, when confronted with an unequal distribution where one participant got most resources, while the others could still obtain the same in the first round than in the second, people rejected the proposition.
degree: MA Public Opinion and Political Behaviour

comment: i did not like the part that the computer randomly chooses a different proposal

demand: whether our political beliefs inform our decisions about equal division of money
comment: i got angry when in a couple of cases I wasn't given any money

demand: To see how people distribute wealth/money when there is no possibility for everyone to have the same amount.
comment: Some people are really egoistic. Of course, everybody allocates the most money to themselves but some people really went crazy and tried to rip off the others.

demand: About deciding whether you split the money equally between the participants or whether you decide to favour only one of them in order to earn more money yourself
comment: It was a nice experiment that surely shows how individuals act when it is a question of choice and money

demand: About how consistent people is regarding redistribution of the wealth and their political opinions. If this is the aim of the experiment it as quite useless as it is not taking into account the personal situation of each participant. Some maybe truly `left` but the fact that probably they are students without incomes has led them to behave quite greedily neither you cannot know if other people is here trying to get money for funding an NGO, for instance, knowing that this `money game` hurts nobody. This experiment only makes sense if what you are trying to prove is that at the end of the day personal reasons have more weight in people`s decisions than their political opinions.
comment: As I have explained. It maybe interesting but without all the variables is useless, fragmentary and probably biased.

demand: Seeing how well people's political stand is reflected in seemingly unrelated decision-making. Whether one sticks to ones principles or tries to get the most money.
comment: It was ok. Frustrating when you're the one allocated the least, because you know you're going to lose, and strangely tempting when you're allocated more than someone else and knows you can either accept and approve of unfairness, or reject and risk being worse off yourself in the next round.
degree: BA Business Management and Modern Languages

demand: Decision making: whether people would be willing to split the money in order for everyone to receive a share or be selfish and take all the money themselves.
comment: The experiment was good, simple and easy. It was interesting to see how people responded to different amounts of money. It was also interesting to see some people chose to share while others did not.

demand: A bit unsure to comment -  could be to do with voting - especially as elections coming up soon!
comment:
I enjoyed the experiment -  interesting to see vast differences in choosing the individual 'bits of the pie'.   Kept mine a bit tighter.

Good instructions.

demand: Game theory with Oligopolies and collusion
How people change dependent on how other people treat them and whether people would self-sacrifice to avoid going to round 2 with a reduced pot
comment:
A little bit slow at times but am assuming that's due to live data being collected. The room was really cold!

The experiment itself was really interesting

demand: The experiment aims to analyse how people make decisions
I enjoyed it, learnt a few things about the way people like to strong-arm others when it comes to dividing money in a society.
comment: Again, good experiment. Although it could tern people into evil capitalist if the experience what i did today.

demand: how to earn the most money while having at least one of the other two members of the group happy as well.
comment: I enjoyed it because my views changed a little bit thorough the experiment.

demand: Whether people will work together and be reasonable to gain a consistent amount of money for all participants or would they aim to get as much as they can individually
comment: Humans can be cruel. Because this was anonymous it gave people the opportunity to be as greedy as they wanted (e.g giving the other participants low score so they get more money)

demand: chance and how much you're willing to give/ how much other sgive you
comment: It was stimulating at times but a little tedious
